# UpSelf — Cursor AI Rules

## Project summary

- **UpSelf** is an RPG-style life productivity iOS app (discipline, quests, HP, six character attributes).
- **Stack:** SwiftUI (UI) + **UIKit Coordinators** for navigation, **SwiftData** (offline-first), **Supabase** (sync/auth via SDK, not from UI), SPM, optional **FamilyControls** (Screen Time).
- **Target:** iOS 17+ (see Xcode project for exact deployment).

---

## Builds and tooling (important)

- **Do not run `xcodebuild`, `swift build`, or automated builds** in the assistant flow unless the user explicitly asks for a build to be run.
- Assume the user **builds, runs, and tests only manually in Xcode**. Prefer describing what to verify rather than invoking build commands.

---

## Architecture: MVVM-C

1. **Views (SwiftUI):** Declarative only. No business logic. User actions go to the **ViewModel**. UI state comes from **SwiftData** (`@Query` / environment) or ViewModel-owned presentation state — not ad hoc globals.
2. **ViewModels (`@Observable` / appropriate pattern):** Presentation logic and SwiftData mutations the feature owns. **No UIKit routing** (no navigation stack ownership). Expose navigation intent via callbacks/closures/delegates for the Coordinator.
3. **Coordinators (UIKit):** Own `UINavigationController`, create `UIHostingController` roots, push/present, inject dependencies into ViewModels.
4. **Data:** Offline-first. Screens read from SwiftData. **Do not call Supabase from Views or ViewModels** — sync belongs in services/repositories when introduced.
5. **DI:** Use **`DependencyContainer`** + **`@Injected`** for shared services (`ModelContainer`, seeding, Supabase, etc.).

### Navigation (strict)

- **Never** use `NavigationLink`, `NavigationStack`, or `@Environment(\.presentationMode)` for **primary app navigation**.
- Route new screens through **`AppCoordinator`** (or feature coordinators) + `UIHostingController`.

### New features (“triad”)

When adding a feature, prefer:

- `Features/<FeatureName>/<FeatureName>View.swift`
- `Features/<FeatureName>/<FeatureName>ViewModel.swift`
- Wire entry in **`AppCoordinator`** (or the relevant coordinator), injecting dependencies.

---

## Folder and file naming

- **App entry / shell:** `UpSelfApp.swift`, `AppCoordinator.swift` at `UpSelf/` root (or as already structured).
- **`Core/`:** Shared infrastructure — `DependencyContainer`, `L10n`, `Theme`, `Data` models & services, `Network`, `AppConfig`, etc.
- **`Features/<Feature>/`:** Feature-specific View + ViewModel (and feature-local helpers if needed).
- **Tests:** `UpSelfTests/`, `UpSelfUITests/` — mirror product naming where useful.

**Naming conventions:**

- Types & files: **PascalCase** (`DashboardView.swift`, `UserProfile.swift`).
- SwiftData models & domain enums: clear, stable names; persisted “kind” fields backed by **`CharacterAttribute`**-style enums (or equivalent), not magic strings in UI.
- Bundle resources: follow Apple conventions (`Localizable.xcstrings`, asset catalogs, fonts registered in Info / target).

---

## Theme and visuals (`AppTheme`)

- **Single source of truth for UI tokens:** `UpSelf/Core/Theme/AppTheme.swift` — **colors, fonts, spacing, radii, strokes, bar heights, shadows**, etc.
- **Do not** scatter raw hex colors, magic `CGFloat`s for padding/corner radius, or ad hoc `Font.custom` calls across views. **Use `AppTheme`** (e.g. `AppTheme.Colors.*`, `AppTheme.Fonts.*`, `AppTheme.Spacing.*`, `AppTheme.Radius.*`).
- **Semantic palette (Amber Terminal):** background `#121212`, cards `#242424`, accent/XP `#FFB000`, alert/HP danger `#FF4500` — expressed via `AppTheme.Colors` (not duplicated in views).
- Custom fonts (e.g. Quantico) stay configured **once** in `AppTheme.Fonts`; views only call `AppTheme.Fonts.ui(...)` / `mono(...)`.

---

## Localization (`L10n`)

- All user-visible strings go through **`UpSelf/Core/L10n.swift`** (`L10n.App`, `L10n.HUD`, `L10n.Stats`, etc.).
- **Workflow for new copy:** (1) Add keys + translations to **`Localizable.xcstrings`**, (2) Add typed accessors in **`L10n.swift`**, (3) Use **`L10n` from Views/ViewModels** — **not** `String(localized: "…")` or raw keys in SwiftUI.
- Keep stat names and other enumerated UI copy aligned with **`CharacterAttribute`** + `L10n.Stats` where applicable.

---

## Data and domain

- **SwiftData** models live under `Core/Data/` (e.g. `UserProfile`, `CharacterStat`, `Quest`). Use enums (`CharacterAttribute`, `QuestRewardTier`, …) for fixed sets of values; persist stable `rawValue`s.
- **Seeding:** `DataSeedService` (first-launch, idempotent) — keep out of Views.
- **No DB migrations or compatibility shims:** Do **not** add SwiftData migration plans, **`@Attribute(originalName:)`** column renames for old stores, one-off “rewrite legacy rows” services, or similar. If the schema or core models change, the workflow is **delete the app / wipe the local store and fresh install** with the new models. Do not invest in upgrade paths unless the user explicitly asks.

---

## Scope and style for AI edits

- Match existing style: imports, naming, and abstraction level in the touched area.
- **Minimal diffs:** change only what the task requires; no drive-by refactors or unrelated files.
- Do **not** add unsolicited documentation files (README/plan) unless the user asks.

---

## Git: branches and commits

Goal: **readable history**, **small reviewable units**, and **modular changes** — avoid “everything in one commit.”

### Branches

- Use **short-lived topic branches** per task or coherent slice of work (not long-running mega-branches).
- Suggested prefixes (pick one style and stay consistent):
  - `feature/<short-name>` — new behavior or screens (e.g. `feature/quest-list`).
  - `fix/<short-name>` — bugfixes.
  - `chore/<short-name>` — tooling, deps, formatting-only, non-product refactors when isolated.
- **Merge to main** when the branch represents one completed story/fix; prefer **linear history** where the team agrees (rebase + merge, or squash-merge with a good message) — follow whatever the repo already uses.

### Commits

- **One logical change per commit** (one concern: e.g. theme tokens only, or L10n keys only, or one feature file). Split large work into **multiple commits** on the same branch rather than one massive diff.
- **Subject line:** **single line**, **~72 characters or less**, imperative mood (“Add…”, “Fix…”, “Refactor…”).
- Prefer **scoped prefixes** so history is scannable and modular:
  - Format: `type(scope): summary`
  - **Types (examples):** `feat`, `fix`, `refactor`, `style` (UI-only), `docs`, `chore`, `test`.
  - **Scope (examples):** `dashboard`, `theme`, `l10n`, `data`, `coordinator`, `deps`.
  - Examples: `feat(dashboard): add stat grid layout`, `fix(l10n): correct Spanish stat label`, `refactor(theme): centralize bar heights in AppTheme`.
- **Body** optional; use when the *why* isn’t obvious. Still keep commits **small** enough that the subject is enough most of the time.
- **Do not** mix unrelated edits in one commit (e.g. don’t combine a feature with a dependency bump and a rename in the same commit).

### For AI-assisted work

- When suggesting or performing git operations, **prefer several small commits** over one large commit when changes span layers (Core vs Feature vs localization).

---

## Quick checklist before finishing a UI task

- [ ] No `NavigationLink` / primary `NavigationStack` routing introduced.
- [ ] Colors/spacing/fonts from **`AppTheme`**.
- [ ] Strings from **`L10n`** + **`Localizable.xcstrings`**.
- [ ] SwiftData reads in Views via **`@Query`** (or injected models) where appropriate.
- [ ] No automated **build** run by the assistant (user builds in Xcode).
- [ ] If committing: **small, scoped commits** with **one-line subjects** (`type(scope): summary`), not one huge catch-all commit.
- [ ] No new **migration / legacy-store** logic for SwiftData — schema changes = fresh install (see **Data and domain**).
